element.name: Watching the Birds by Windsockers, Traditional Cache (2/1.5)

long-description.p:
Malahide Estuary stretches from Malahide eastwards to Swords.
The outer part of the estuary is mostly cut off from the sea by a large sand spit, known as "the island”. It drains almost completely at low tide, exposing sand and mud flats.
This estuary is an important wintering bird site where a number of birds can be seen including Brent Geese, Great Crested Grebe, Mute Swan, Shelduck, Pochard, Red-breasted Merganser, Oystercatcher, And Golden Plover.

The Brent population is of international importance. The high numbers of diving birds reflects the lagoon-type nature of the inner estuary. The head of the estuary, traditionally known as Swords estuary, holds a large flock of Mute Swans which have been studied for many years as part of a research programe on the swans of County Dublin.
Many of them have white numbered rings on their legs. Indeed, Mute Swans ringed in Dublin as part of this program have been seen as far east as Wales, as far south as Wexford and as far west as Cork.
The Cache is a small micro container please re-hide it well to prevent the many muggles from discovering it.

ul.li:
2010-06-14T19:00:00Z : Didn't find it by RosMcC
I followed the GPS into the woods, and then walked straight out the other side and back to the car. Dozens of ivy covered trees, and with the erratic signal it could have been any one of them. Also ivy six inches deep all over the ground. The words "needle" and "haystack" came to mind. Definitely needed a hint here, even if only to say what level I should be looking at. There were other caches to find, so I didn't linger for what could have been a very long search.

2010-06-09T19:00:00Z : Didn't find it by Crannyn
With 2 juniors , the patience was running out. So will have to re visit with a few clues from previous logs [:(]

2010-05-15T19:00:00Z : Found it by Alastair74
Found while spending the day in Dublin for the WWFM with Wildfowler TFTC

2010-05-15T19:00:00Z : Found it by wildfowler
Found on a caching weekend around Dublin with Alastair74! TNLNSL TFTC

2010-04-04T19:00:00Z : Didn't find it by Jumpin Jiminie
No joy with this one...just too many places to look.
Defo merits more than 2 stars.
I will return though.
Jamie
